<tr><td class='easySpoilerRow' colspan='2' style=''><div id='spoilerDiv4e4d8003' class='easySpoilerSpoils'  style='display:none; white-space:wrap; overflow:auto; vertical-align:middle;'>
</p>
<p>No. Call the current six numbers <em>a</em><sub>1</sub> &#8230; <em>a</em><sub>6</sub>. Now <em>I</em> = <em>a</em><sub>1</sub> &#8211; <em>a</em><sub>2</sub> + <em>a</em><sub>3</sub> &#8211; <em>a</em><sub>4</sub> + <em>a</em><sub>5</sub> &#8211; <em>a</em><sub>6</sub> is initially 2, and <em>I</em> will remain unchanged no matter what we do. So there&#8217;s no way to reach <em>I</em> = 0.</p>
<p>Via Arthur Engel, <em>Problem-Solving Strategies</em>, 1999.</p>
<p>
